# Challenge 1 - Cloud Agnostic / Hybrid Deployments

Customer "ACME" has a Kafka instance running on-premises and would like
to migrate the apps to cloud to offload some of the processing
workloads. As part of the strategy for migrating to cloud, ACME is
considering running a hybrid architecture. This will comprise running
the on-premise and cloud application both of which have a high
dependency on Kafka.

The key business requirement is to keep the application architecture
cloud agnostic as much as possible so deployment to multi-cloud is easy
and seamless.

This is a very typical scenario with the Financial Services sector who
have embraced the Kafka Distributed Streaming Platform as part of
applications running at high scale.

## Scenario

You have been requested by ACME to present a proof of concept on how the
below applications from ACME will run on Azure:

1.  BadgeApp is a gamification service that ACME wants to open up to
    third-party data producers in the future. To cut down on development
    costs when this happens they want to enforce a common payload format
    now.
2.  StackApp will be a stream of posts and comments from StackOverflow
    that ACME wants to enrich with textual analysis using an external
    API in the cloud.

## Key Requirements

Customer IT Department managing the apps have asked you to create a new
POC on cloud honoring the requirements stated in the User Story.

  - The application infrastructure needs to be cloud agnostic.
  - Management would like to avoid to have to buy additional licenses to
    run the solution.
  - Use of [Lambda
    Architecture](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lambda_architecture) to
    process data as soon as it arrives.
  - As data of any kind is important, you are required to store all the
    raw and unprocessed data in a location to allow analysis at a later
    stage.
  - Store the results of the enrichment process for future visualization
    and analysis.

## Lambda Architecture

The below image is a representation of a typical Lambda architecture.
The architecture attempts to balance latency, throughput, and
fault-tolerance by using batch processing to provide comprehensive and
accurate views of batch data, while simultaneously using real-time
stream processing to provide views of online data.

architecture](data:image/jpeg;base64,

#### Task 4 - Comply with message schema

![Infra-label](data:image/jpeg;base64,
"Infra-label")
![Dev-label](data:image/jpeg;base64,
"Dev-label")

Applications and stream processing pipelines that subscribe to a data
stream should be confident that a producer upstream **shouldn't** send
them data they can’t handle. In this case a shared schema store, where
the reader is assured to be able to deserialize all data coming from
upstream writers, makes your data pipelines much more robust.

In this task you are required to build a schema store to validate the
messages being sent to Kafka. Below is a typical record that you would
see and the sample AVRO schema to be used.

##### Payload Sample

``` json
{
    "Id": 9,
    "Name": "Teacher",
    "UserId": 164,
    "DisplayName": "dragonmantank",
    "Reputation": 7636,
    "UpVotes": 56,
    "DownVotes": 3
}
```

##### AVRO Schema

``` json
{
    "type":"record",
    "name":"BadgeEvent",
    "namespace":"badgeevent",
    "fields":
    [
        {"name":"id", "type":"string"},
        {"name":"name", "type":"string"},
        {"name":"userId", "type":"string"},
        {"name":"displayName", "type":"string"},
        {"name":"reputation", "type":"string"},
        {"name":"upVotes", "type":"int"},
        {"name":"downVotes", "type":"int"},
        {"name":"processedDate", "type":"string"}
    ]
}
```

Coach to verify - Show that schema registry is created with a valid url

#### Task 6 - Begin creating listener solution

![Dev-label](data:image/jpeg;base64,
"Dev-label")
![Data-label](data:image/jpeg;base64,
"Data-label")

Here, you will be using the on-prem StackApp solution which sends
payloads of multiple types to the Kafka topic called "events". Due to
application constraints all messages sent to this topic are in JSON
format.

In this task you are required to create a solution that performs stream
processing of messages that are being sent to the topic "events" by
StackApp. At this point, you only need to display a sample of the
stream.

The StackApp solution deployed by your coach will produce 3 type of
messages

1.  StackOverflow post message: This contains details about a post made
    on StackoverFlow
    
    ``` json
    {
        "Id":"1",
        "Body": "This is a post",
        "OwnerUserId": "21",
        "Type": "Post",
        "CreatedAt": "2008-09-06 08:09:52.330"
    }
    ```

2.  Vote message: This contains details about a vote made on
    StackoverFlow post
    
    ``` json
    {
        "Id": "2",
        "UserId": "435",
        "PostId": "2342",
        "VoteTypeId": "3",
        "Type": "Vote",
        "CreatedAt": "20012-09-16 05:06:55.123"
    }
    ```

3.  Comment message: This contains details about a comment made on
    StackoverFlow post
    
    ``` json
    {
        "Id": "3",
        "UserId": "35",
        "PostId": "1234",
        "Text": "This is a comment",
        "Type": "Comment",
        "CreatedAt": "20012-09-16 05:06:55.123"
    }
    ```

Coach to verify - Able to see some messages being streamed

#### Task 7 - Apply text analysis to the stream of messages

![Dev-label](data:image/jpeg;base64,
"Dev-label")
![Data-label](data:image/jpeg;base64,
"Data-label")

As part of the the POC you are asked to implement key phrase extraction
for messages being sent into the "events" Kafka topic. To achieve this
you need to add some code to the previously created consumer solution.

You would need to call a key phrase extraction API endpoint with the
input data for Post and Comment message types and enrich the original
data with the results received from the API call as shown in the samples
below.

POST the Post/Comment objects in JSON form (either one at a time or
arrays of objects) to any of these endpoints

``` bash
https://ohkl-kp0.azurewebsites.net/api/KeyPhraseFunc
https://ohkl-kp1.azurewebsites.net/api/KeyPhraseFunc
https://ohkl-kp2.azurewebsites.net/api/KeyPhraseFunc
```

Sample Input:

``` json
{
    "Id": "433",
    "Body": "This is a really good post.",
    "OwnerUserId": "21",
    "Type": "Post",
    "CreatedAt": "2018-09-06 08:09:52.330"
}
```

Sample Enriched Output:

``` json
{
    "Id": "433",
    "Body": "This is a really good post.",
    "OwnerUserId": "21",
    "Type": "Post",
    "CreatedAt": "2018-09-06 08:09:52.330",
    "keyPhrases": [
        "good post"
    ]
}
```

Coach to verify - Albe to see some messages being streamed with the
added output

#### Task 8 - Write to database

![Dev-label](data:image/jpeg;base64,
"Dev-label")
![Data-label](data:image/jpeg;base64,
"Data-label")

You are asked to create a near-real time updated tag cloud with the most
used keywords. Modify your solution created in the previous task so that
the extracted key phrases and the timestamp are stored into a database
of your choice.

Depending on your destination data store, you might want to use a format
similar to one of the following:

| ts                      | keyphrase |
| :---------------------- | --------: |
| 2008-09-06 08:09:52.330 |    sample |
| 2008-09-06 08:09:52.330 |   message |

``` json
[
    { "ts": "2008-09-06 08:09:52.330", "keyphrase": "sample" },
    { "ts": "2008-09-06 08:09:52.330", "keyphrase": "message" }
]
```

Coach to verify - Look for the Messages stored in database
